<v ->Yeah, I've had the fortunate opportunity to actually live</v>

19
00:00:59.509 --> 00:01:01.770
in a number of countries in Africa and the Middle East

20
00:01:01.770 --> 00:01:04.373
for many years and have traveled through them

21
00:01:04.373 --> 00:01:08.000
for many years. Many of these countries were at war,

22
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.293
so I had the opportunity to see hundreds of thousands

23
00:01:11.293 --> 00:01:13.849
of traumatized people. I saw populations that were

24
00:01:13.849 --> 00:01:18.368
traumatized rather than individuals as a clinician.

25
00:01:18.368 --> 00:01:21.621
That gave me a different perspective on trauma.

26
00:01:21.621 --> 00:01:25.546
<v Voiceover>Would you say that if you take war</v>

27
00:01:25.546 --> 00:01:30.527
out of the equation, the traumas that you see in human kind

28
00:01:30.527 --> 00:01:34.385
are fairly well balanced,

29
00:01:34.385 --> 00:01:38.097
are fairly similar regardless of the culture?

30
00:01:38.097 --> 00:01:39.793
Do we all experience more or less the same things,

31
00:01:39.793 --> 00:01:42.289
or is it very culture-specific, the types of trauma

32
00:01:42.289 --> 00:01:44.499
we experience?

33
00:01:44.499 --> 00:01:45.998
<v ->There's a little bit of both.</v>

34
00:01:45.998 --> 00:01:49.226
This is what my take on trauma is, from having really

35
00:01:49.226 --> 00:01:52.198
traveled to many, many countries around the world and worked

36
00:01:52.198 --> 00:01:55.291
with many populations, is that trauma

37
00:01:55.291 --> 00:02:00.027
literally is a natural experience of the human person,

38
00:02:00.027 --> 00:02:03.302
just as it it's any other animal or plant.

39
00:02:03.302 --> 00:02:06.374
If you consider that we're a living organism on the planet,

40
00:02:06.374 --> 00:02:10.566
not only are we traumatized, but we are genetically encoded

41
00:02:10.566 --> 00:02:14.438
to endure that trauma, survive it, and I believe even learn

42
00:02:14.438 --> 00:02:16.710
from the trauma, and that's what the process of

43
00:02:16.710 --> 00:02:19.845
evolution has been. I believe that trauma's absolutely

44
00:02:19.845 --> 00:02:22.299
natural to the human organism just as it is

45
00:02:22.299 --> 00:02:23.632
to any organism on the planet.

46
00:02:23.632 --> 00:02:25.147
<v Voiceover>To an orchid.</v>

47
00:02:25.147 --> 00:02:27.588
<v ->Exactly.</v>

48
00:02:27.588 --> 00:02:30.553
There is no animal that you couldn't find that's available

49
00:02:30.553 --> 00:02:32.729
to be being traumatized throughout all of life.

50
00:02:32.729 --> 00:02:34.785
The only thing we've done as humans is we've socialized

51
00:02:34.785 --> 00:02:38.241
it more, but in general, even if we didn't socialize trauma,

52
00:02:38.241 --> 00:02:40.929
we'd still have to put up with hurricanes and earthquakes

53
00:02:40.929 --> 00:02:45.394
and devastation and death,

54
00:02:45.394 --> 00:02:46.416
which is natural to us.

55
00:02:46.416 --> 00:02:48.085
<v Voiceover>So these are normal types of trauma</v>

56
00:02:48.085 --> 00:02:50.464
you experience in the earth experience,

57
00:02:50.464 --> 00:02:54.101
but really now what we're seeing is more self-induced types

58
00:02:54.101 --> 00:02:56.949
of trauma to our own societies through

59
00:02:56.949 --> 00:02:58.709
many different sources.

60
00:02:58.709 --> 00:02:59.392
<v ->Right.</v>

61
00:02:59.392 --> 00:03:01.994
<v Voiceover>We'll start getting into some of what you're</v>

62
00:03:01.994 --> 00:03:05.920
seeing by way of beyond and above the ordinary sources

63
00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:08.469
of trauma, more self-inflicted traumas.

64
00:03:08.469 --> 00:03:09.461
<v ->Right. Exactly.</v>

65
00:03:09.461 --> 00:03:11.594
<v Voiceover>What are you experiencing and noticing?</v>

66
00:03:11.594 --> 00:03:12.960
<v ->Well, usually what happens,</v>

67
00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:16.202
let's take war as an example,

68
00:03:16.202 --> 00:03:19.231
if war occurs and there's a tremendous amount of violence

69
00:03:19.231 --> 00:03:22.849
and traumatizing of people, five years after that,

70
00:03:22.849 --> 00:03:24.777
studies have already demonstrated that you'll have

71
00:03:24.777 --> 00:03:27.721
a much higher increase in domestic violence

72
00:03:27.721 --> 00:03:30.761
and social traumas. You'd have a lot of childhood abuse,

73
00:03:30.761 --> 00:03:34.088
a lot of domestic violence going on, and the ways that

74
00:03:34.088 --> 00:03:38.270
we express trauma socially is by demeaning human beings,

75
00:03:38.270 --> 00:03:41.427
or trying to prove ourselves to be better,

76
00:03:41.427 --> 00:03:44.404
creating safety in some way, and safety for us

77
00:03:44.404 --> 00:03:48.296
means being in control, and so if I'm out of control,

78
00:03:48.296 --> 00:03:50.931
I will do something to make sure I can submit

79
00:03:50.931 --> 00:03:54.483
the other person or other family members or other people

80
00:03:54.483 --> 00:03:57.171
in the society back into control again,

81
00:03:57.171 --> 00:04:00.147
and therefore I can produce safety for myself and

82
00:04:00.147 --> 00:04:04.073
feel more relaxed. All those various forms of demeaning

83
00:04:04.073 --> 00:04:07.325
or diminishing other human beings is in fact

84
00:04:07.325 --> 00:04:09.661
re-introducing trauma,

85
00:04:09.661 --> 00:04:13.082
a superior-inferior type of behavior pattern.

86
00:04:13.082 --> 00:04:15.693
<v Voiceover>How is this expressing itself in the culture</v>

87
00:04:15.693 --> 00:04:18.040
of the Western world? We're in the United States

88
00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:20.386
as we speak. How does it express itself?

89
00:04:20.386 --> 00:04:22.361
<v ->Well, that's one of the complaints that we have in</v>

90
00:04:22.361 --> 00:04:24.725
the Western world, or the United States as an example.

91
00:04:24.725 --> 00:04:26.517
You can find globally that people say,

92
00:04:26.517 --> 00:04:29.034
well, Americans are very self-centered.

93
00:04:29.034 --> 00:04:32.522
Now I'm not suggesting that that's necessarily the case,

94
00:04:32.522 --> 00:04:34.751
because I'm not going to put down the United States,

95
00:04:34.751 --> 00:04:37.823
but we, like every other nation on the planet, look for

96
00:04:37.823 --> 00:04:41.194
superiority, and we look for it for the sake of safety.

97
00:04:41.194 --> 00:04:45.546
In that process, we actually can re-introduce or produce

98
00:04:45.546 --> 00:04:50.206
danger by taking third-world nations

99
00:04:50.206 --> 00:04:51.614
and controlling them,

100
00:04:51.614 --> 00:04:54.249
controlling their economic wealth, controlling the way

101
00:04:54.249 --> 00:04:56.393
they have international agreements.

102
00:04:56.393 --> 00:04:59.891
All of those behaviors are about making sure that we feel

103
00:04:59.891 --> 00:05:01.262
safe as a nation.

104
00:05:01.262 --> 00:05:02.915
<v Voiceover>And as in most things, when you try to</v>

105
00:05:02.915 --> 00:05:05.955
control another entity, there's usually a backlash.

106
00:05:05.955 --> 00:05:08.387
<v ->Of course, there has to be. We've seen this as</v>

107
00:05:08.387 --> 00:05:11.788
a repetition in the United States and other countries.

108
00:05:11.788 --> 00:05:16.109
All types of colonialization had some sort of backlash.

109
00:05:16.109 --> 00:05:19.073
Africa and Latin America are both suffering still severely

110
00:05:19.073 --> 00:05:22.438
from the trauma of colonialization. And how does that

111
00:05:22.438 --> 00:05:25.382
get expressed? By anger and resentment towards

112
00:05:25.382 --> 00:05:27.974
the first-world nations that colonized them,

113
00:05:27.974 --> 00:05:30.246
but yet at the same time the need to have relationships

114
00:05:30.246 --> 00:05:32.379
with those first-world nations.

115
00:05:32.379 --> 00:05:33.947
It's no different than a family trauma.

116
00:05:33.947 --> 00:05:35.568
<v Voiceover>I was going to say, in a family,</v>

117
00:05:35.568 --> 00:05:37.029
it's a very similar dynamic.

118
00:05:37.029 --> 00:05:39.419
<v ->Right. If the children are traumatized by the parents,</v>

119
00:05:39.419 --> 00:05:41.893
the children still need the parents. At the same time,

120
00:05:41.893 --> 00:05:44.283
they resent the parents. We're just talking about it

121
00:05:44.283 --> 00:05:46.629
on a more global scale.

122
00:05:46.629 --> 00:05:49.531
<v Voiceover>And when you have this,</v>

123
00:05:49.531 --> 00:05:53.157
you have a very interesting contribution in this field

124
00:05:53.157 --> 00:05:56.613
because yours is how to release that kind of excessive

125
00:05:56.613 --> 00:05:59.045
energy that occurs with trauma.

126
00:05:59.045 --> 00:06:01.690
<v ->Right. Here's what happened to me.</v>

127
00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:04.454
I was in Africa and the Middle East for many years,

128
00:06:04.454 --> 00:06:07.163
and I saw over and over and over thousands of

129
00:06:07.163 --> 00:06:10.619
traumatized people, and I began to recognize, sort-of

130
00:06:10.619 --> 00:06:13.520
unconsciously at first, that there were certain patterns

131
00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:15.813
that were being repeated, that had nothing to do with

132
00:06:15.813 --> 00:06:19.056
cultural, or language or anything about the particular

133
00:06:19.056 --> 00:06:21.797
backgrounds. These patterns were being repeated

134
00:06:21.797 --> 00:06:25.285
because I was watching the human species

135
00:06:25.285 --> 00:06:27.958
experience trauma, and I was watching how the human

136
00:06:27.958 --> 00:06:32.949
species was re-structuring itself to not only

137
00:06:32.949 --> 00:06:36.864
endure the trauma but survive it. This is when I began

138
00:06:36.864 --> 00:06:38.581
to see these patterns.

139
00:06:38.581 --> 00:06:41.824
What I did was I studied what is the pattern of the human

140
00:06:41.824 --> 00:06:44.000
organism, or the human animal if you will,

141
00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.171
in the wild. How do they

142
00:06:48.171 --> 00:06:49.707
protect themselves when

143
00:06:49.707 --> 00:06:51.744
they're being threatened to death?

144
00:06:51.744 --> 00:06:53.248
<v Voiceover>And what did you find?</v>

145
00:06:53.248 --> 00:06:56.096
<v ->What I discovered is that there's a whole pattern</v>

146
00:06:56.096 --> 00:07:00.373
of muscles in the body related to the brain that are

147
00:07:00.373 --> 00:07:03.147
an instinctual sense of muscles that cause us to

148
00:07:03.147 --> 00:07:05.920
defend or protect ourselves. So as an example,

149
00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:08.869
if we heard a loud sound right now, outside,

150
00:07:08.869 --> 00:07:12.272
both of us instinctually would jerk forward,

151
00:07:12.272 --> 00:07:14.021
in a pulling motion.

152
00:07:14.021 --> 00:07:18.170
The automatic and extreme example of that would be

153
00:07:18.170 --> 00:07:21.797
rolling up into the fetal position, because the underbelly

154
00:07:21.797 --> 00:07:24.901
of our human animal structure is the most vulnerable

155
00:07:24.901 --> 00:07:27.162
part of our structure. So we're going to protect that

156
00:07:27.162 --> 00:07:29.552
underbelly, but we're going to do that instinctually,

157
00:07:29.552 --> 00:07:32.592
much like blinking our eyes. You won't think to jerk

158
00:07:32.592 --> 00:07:35.194
forward; you willl just automatically do that.

159
00:07:35.194 --> 00:07:37.957
Well, that's connected to a certain part of the brain

160
00:07:37.957 --> 00:07:41.413
where that's an autonomic response, and it's autonomic

161
00:07:41.413 --> 00:07:43.727
because if you had to think about, you would probably

162
00:07:43.727 --> 00:07:46.746
be dead, in the two seconds that it took to think about

163
00:07:46.746 --> 00:07:49.861
doing that. So, if it's a reflexive reaction, then you're

164
00:07:49.861 --> 00:07:52.474
actually guaranteed greater safety.

165
00:07:52.474 --> 00:07:56.533
What happens with that is as we pull forward like that,

166
00:07:56.533 --> 00:08:01.184
let's say I had prolonged trauma of abuse a child,

167
00:08:01.184 --> 00:08:04.160
as an example, my father beating me or something like that.

168
00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:07.637
I will constantly keep repeating that pattern over and over

169
00:08:07.637 --> 00:08:11.136
and over, so now it becomes part of the ingrained muscular

170
00:08:11.136 --> 00:08:15.434
pattern along with the neural pattern of the traumatic event

171
00:08:15.434 --> 00:08:18.517
so that any time I see somebody who has my father's eyes,

172
00:08:18.517 --> 00:08:21.069
or his voice, or something like that, I'll begin to repeat

173
00:08:21.069 --> 00:08:23.338
that pattern unconsciously.

174
00:08:23.338 --> 00:08:27.477
Once I saw that pattern happen in these traumatized people,

175
00:08:27.477 --> 00:08:31.640
constantly repeating a pulling forward,

176
00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:34.048
sort of a fetal position protection,

177
00:08:34.048 --> 00:08:37.536
I just asked myself, well I know that the neural network

178
00:08:37.536 --> 00:08:41.301
is attached to certain, or all muscle patterns in the body,

179
00:08:41.301 --> 00:08:43.989
and that neural network is a dual pathway,

180
00:08:43.989 --> 00:08:47.434
basically the central nervous system can communicate

181
00:08:47.434 --> 00:08:50.296
from the body up to the brain

182
00:08:50.296 --> 00:08:52.312
or from the brain down to the body.

183
00:08:52.312 --> 00:08:53.378
<v Voiceover>Mm hmm.</v>

184
00:08:53.378 --> 00:08:56.696
<v ->The question became to me, what if I happened to be</v>

185
00:08:56.696 --> 00:09:00.119
able to relax the body? If I can relax the body, can I

186
00:09:00.119 --> 00:09:03.181
change the brain? And we already know we can do this.

187
00:09:03.181 --> 00:09:06.093
You can get a massage, and the massage therapist doesn't

188
00:09:06.093 --> 00:09:08.781
talk to you at all about what the problem is that you had

189
00:09:08.781 --> 00:09:11.970
when you come in; you were full of anxiety as an example.

190
00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:14.709
You can leave the massage session and absolutely

191
00:09:14.709 --> 00:09:17.003
have reduced all of your anxiety, not even remembering

192
00:09:17.003 --> 00:09:19.189
what you were worrying about when you came in.

193
00:09:19.189 --> 00:09:21.952
So we know that we can do something to the body

194
00:09:21.952 --> 00:09:25.248
that affects the brain. My challenge to me,

195
00:09:25.248 --> 00:09:28.405
when I saw thousands of traumatized people, is,

196
00:09:28.405 --> 00:09:30.325
when I don't speak their language, I don't know

197
00:09:30.325 --> 00:09:33.226
their culture, and I can't give each one of them two years

198
00:09:33.226 --> 00:09:35.840
of psychotherapy to help them heal from trauma,

199
00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:38.784
so can I make some intervention in their body

200
00:09:38.784 --> 00:09:41.301
that they could actually repeat themselves

201
00:09:41.301 --> 00:09:44.165
and actually start to reduce their trauma symptoms.

202
00:09:44.165 --> 00:09:47.237
And that's how I developed the trauma reducing exercises.

203
00:09:47.237 --> 00:09:51.791
<v Voiceover>Where did you first read about, hear about</v>

204
00:09:51.791 --> 00:09:55.078
this type of exercise which requires the body to actually

205
00:09:55.078 --> 00:09:58.235
shake or tremble? Which of course, naturally, right after

206
00:09:58.235 --> 00:10:00.454
a traumatic event, we do shake and tremble.

207
00:10:00.454 --> 00:10:01.254
<v ->Right.</v>

208
00:10:01.254 --> 00:10:03.142
<v Voiceover>What's happening there?</v>

209
00:10:03.142 --> 00:10:05.872
<v ->There's very little literature on it, and I actually went</v>

210
00:10:05.872 --> 00:10:09.712
to the literature in animals, actually, to look at what

211
00:10:09.712 --> 00:10:11.291
was happening to animals.

212
00:10:11.291 --> 00:10:14.430
Much of the literature has already demonstrated that

213
00:10:14.430 --> 00:10:18.399
after traumatic events, most mammal species will tremor

214
00:10:18.399 --> 00:10:20.565
organically through their whole body,

215
00:10:20.565 --> 00:10:24.049
and the implication of this is that the tremoring is helping

216
00:10:24.049 --> 00:10:28.051
to take the animal out of

217
00:10:28.051 --> 00:10:29.417
their freeze response,

218
00:10:29.417 --> 00:10:32.702
or their trauma response, and help restore the homeostasis,

219
00:10:32.702 --> 00:10:36.286
or the balance in the body. What I realized was, that while

220
00:10:36.286 --> 00:10:39.475
I was living in war, not only in war. We have common

221
00:10:39.475 --> 00:10:42.387
examples of that in our cultures at large, but when we

222
00:10:42.387 --> 00:10:46.056
get anxious or nervous, we begin to tremor, even if

223
00:10:46.056 --> 00:10:48.787
it's something positive, like you're getting married.

224
00:10:48.787 --> 00:10:51.774
You could find that your hands are tremoring, or your knees

225
00:10:51.774 --> 00:10:54.323
are tremoring, not because you're afraid, but you're

226
00:10:54.323 --> 00:10:58.377
overcharged. Basically the body has too much charge in it,

227
00:10:58.377 --> 00:11:01.245
and the tremor is the natural release valve to actually

228
00:11:01.245 --> 00:11:04.445
reduce the charge back down to normal.

229
00:11:04.445 --> 00:11:07.091
Here we have a lot of traumatized people, or people

230
00:11:07.091 --> 00:11:09.907
who are scared. If your boss is yelling at you, your voice

231
00:11:09.907 --> 00:11:14.163
might quiver. If you are holding back crying or sadness,

232
00:11:14.163 --> 00:11:16.605
your jaw will often quiver.

233
00:11:16.605 --> 00:11:18.995
People after a car accident, even if they're not injured,

234
00:11:18.995 --> 00:11:23.346
will just come out and say I shook uncontrollably all over.

235
00:11:23.346 --> 00:11:26.333
Well, what we did is we defined that shaking as

236
00:11:26.333 --> 00:11:29.021
a pathological expression of the trauma,

237
00:11:29.021 --> 00:11:32.520
rather than potential positive effect of a restoration

238
00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:34.066
of the homeostasis in the body.

239
00:11:34.066 --> 00:11:34.952
<v Voiceover>Right.</v>

240
00:11:34.952 --> 00:11:37.565
<v ->So when I lived in war enough, and I certainly tremored</v>

241
00:11:37.565 --> 00:11:40.850
enough, and I certainly lived with thousands of people

242
00:11:40.850 --> 00:11:44.338
that were tremoring, I began to equate that the tremoring

243
00:11:44.338 --> 00:11:47.335
that mammals do must be the same thing that's going on

244
00:11:47.335 --> 00:11:50.834
in humans, although we're defining it as a pathology.

245
00:11:50.834 --> 00:11:54.674
So I began to develop exercises to help actually evoke

246
00:11:54.674 --> 00:11:58.727
those tremors. I wanted to see if we evoked the tremors,

247
00:11:58.727 --> 00:12:01.586
and we actually stay in the tremoring response,

248
00:12:01.586 --> 00:12:05.714
